---
/**
 * Visible pricing statement, required on every product page.
 *
 * The exact sentence in PRICING_STATEMENT is what the Offer schema mirrors.
 * The qualifier below it is not decoration: it is what keeps the $0.30 figure
 * honest, by stating plainly that it is a volume starting point rather than a
 * price anyone will pay at any quantity.
 */
import { PRICING_STATEMENT } from '../data/product-content';
---

<aside class="price-note" aria-labelledby="pricing-heading">
  <h2 class="price-note__heading" id="pricing-heading">Pricing</h2>
  <p class="price-note__statement">{PRICING_STATEMENT}</p>
  <p class="price-note__qualifier">
    That $0.30 figure is a starting point for qualifying large-volume orders — not a fixed price,
    and not what a small run costs. Setup work (dieline, plates, press make-ready) is spread across
    the run, so the per-piece price rises as quantity falls. Specialty board, added inserts, and
    premium finishes all move it as well. The only way to get your number is a quote against your
    actual specification.
  </p>
  <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/request-a-quote/">Get a price for your specification</a>
</aside>

<style>
  .price-note {
    padding: var(--s-6);
    background: var(--c-paper-warm);
    border: 1px solid var(--c-border);
    border-inline-start: 3px solid var(--c-signal-700);
    border-radius: var(--r-lg);
  }

  .price-note__heading {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: var(--t-xs);
    font-weight: 650;
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-caps);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--c-signal-700);
    margin-block-end: var(--s-3);
  }

  .price-note__statement {
    font-size: var(--t-lg);
    line-height: var(--lh-snug);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--c-ink-900);
    max-width: 46ch;
  }

  .price-note__qualifier {
    margin-block: var(--s-4) var(--s-5);
    font-size: var(--t-base);
    color: var(--c-text-muted);
    max-width: 62ch;
  }
</style>
